Yes — many animals can detect physiological and behavioral cues associated with fear or stress, often far better than humans consciously notice.

They may pick up on:

* posture changes,
* muscle tension,
* movement patterns,
* breathing rate,
* vocal tone,
* scent/pheromonal changes,
* heart-rate-linked behavior,
* eye movement,
* or hesitation.

Predators and social animals especially evolve sensitivity to state changes because it matters for:

* threat assessment,
* hunting,
* hierarchy,
* bonding,
* and survival.

Humans do versions of this too, often subconsciously. People can sometimes “feel” nervousness, aggression, calmness, or confidence before they can explain why. That’s usually not supernatural — it’s rapid pattern integration from many subtle signals.

And attention plays a role again:
when someone is highly fearful, their behavior often becomes less fluid and more constrained, which changes the signal landscape around them. Calm regulated states tend to produce clearer perception and smoother movement, which other organisms respond to differently.